8"}, {"input": "grid = [[10,20,30],[20,30,40],[30,40,50]]", "output": "249"}], "query": "You are an expert Python programmer. You will be given a question (problem specification) and will generate a correct Python program that matches the specification and passes all tests.\n\n### Question:\nYou are given an n x n grid where we place some 1 x 1 x 1 cubes that are axis-aligned with the x, y, and z axes.\nEach value v = grid[i][j] represents a tower of v cubes placed on top of the cell (i, j).\nWe view the projection of these cubes onto the xy, yz, and zx planes.\nA projection is like a shadow, that maps our 3-dimensional figure to a 2-dimensional plane. We are viewing the \"shadow\" when looking at the cubes from the top, the front, and the side.\nReturn the total area of all three projections.\n \nExample 1:\n\n\nInput: grid = [[1,2],[3,4]]\nOutput: 17\nExplanation: Here are the three projections (\"shadows\") of the shape made with each axis-aligned plane.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: grid = [[2]]\nOutput: 5\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: grid = [[1,0],[0,2]]\nOutput: 8\n\n \nConstraints:\n\nn == grid.length == grid[i].length\n1 <= n <= 50\n0 <= grid[i][j] <= 50\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def projectionArea(self, grid: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def projectionArea(self, grid: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        n = len(grid)\n        \n        # Top view: count all non-zero cells\n        top_view = sum(1 for i in range(n) for j in range(n) if grid[i][j] > 0)\n        \n        # Front view: sum of the maximum values of each row\n        front_view = sum(max(row) for row in grid)\n        \n        # Side view: sum of the maximum values of each column\n        side_view = sum(max(grid[i][j] for i in range(n)) for j in range(n))\n        \n        # Total projection area\n        return top_view + front_view + side_view\n```\n\nThis solution calculates the total area of the projections of the 3D grid onto the three planes:\n\n1. **Top view**: Count all the cells that have at least one cube (i.e., all cells with values greater than 0).\n2. **Front view**: Sum the maximum values of each row, as this represents the tallest tower seen from the front for each row.\n3. **Side view**: Sum the maximum values of each column, as this represents the tallest tower seen from the side for each column.\n\nThe function then returns the sum of these three views, which gives the total projection area.", "estimated_date": 1533427200000}